\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
\b Grayscale conversion\b0\par
Grayscale is simply converting images from colored to black and white. It is normally used to reduce computation complexity in machine learning algorithms.\par
Since most pictures don\rquote t need color to be recognized, it is wise to use grayscale, which reduces the number of pixels in an image, thus, reducing the computations required.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1 Execute the code below to convert the original image to grayscale:\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1 gray_image = skimage.color.rgb2gray(image)\par
plt.imshow(gray_image, cmap = 'gray')\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1 A few examples to use grayscale include: traffic lights, healthcare diagnosis, autonomous vehicles, agriculture, etc. \par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\b Normalization\b0\par
Also referred to as data re-scaling, it is the process of projecting image data pixels (intensity) to a predefined range (usually (0,1) or (-1, 1)). This is commonly used on different data formats, and you want to normalize all of them to apply the same algorithms over them.\par
Normalization is usually applied to convert an image\rquote s pixel values to a typical or more familiar sense.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\ul Its benefits include:\ulnone\par

\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\ul Fairness across all images \ulnone - For example, scaling all images to an equal range of [0,1] or [-1,1] allows all images to contribute equally to the total loss rather than when other images have high and low pixels ranges give strong and weak loss, respectively.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par

\pard{\pntext\f3\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf3\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl276\slmult1\ul Provides a standard learning rate \ulnone - Since high pixel images require a low learning rate and low pixel images high learning rate, re-scaling helps provide a standard learning rate for all images.\par

\pard\sl276\slmult1\par
